    "description":  "Find out about flexible working ambassador schools.",
    "details":  {
                    "attachments":  [

                                    ],
                    "body":  "\u003cdiv class=\"govspeak\"\u003e\u003ch2 id=\"overview\"\u003eOverview\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFlexible working practices can:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003ehelp to recruit, retain and motivate teachers\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003esupport schools to deploy their staff effectively and efficiently\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eimprove staff wellbeing\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003epromote equality of opportunity and diversity in teaching\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIn March 2021, the Department for Education (\u003cabbr title=\"Department for Education\"\u003eDfE\u003c/abbr\u003e) appointed 8 flexible working ambassador schools across England.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWe selected the flexible working ambassador schools following a competitive application process. They were funded for delivery until December 2022.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"role-and-responsibilities-of-flexible-working-ambassador-schools\"\u003eRole and responsibilities of flexible working ambassador schools\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFlexible working ambassador schools were responsible for:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eawareness raising, acting as influencers, attending and hosting peer-to-peer training events and working with local networks to champion flexible working\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eproviding practical support to schools through coaching and advising\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003esupporting participant schools to address challenges related to flexible working, offer more opportunities for flexible working, and embed a positive culture towards it\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003erecruiting at least 5 schools across their region to provide one-to-one, bespoke support from April 2021 to December 2022, including a school most in need of support. Flexible working ambassador schools were able to use their discretion to decide what constituted greatest need in their region. This could include a school that was within the top-30th percentile in relation to pupils on pupil premium, or a school that faced challenges in relation to recruitment or retention\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"contact\"\u003eContact\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor more information about flexible working ambassador schools, email \u003ca href=\"mailto:FlexibleWorking.RESOURCES@education.gov.uk\" class=\"govuk-link\"\u003eFlexibleWorking.RESOURCES@education.gov.uk\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e",
